[src:peg-parser/comparison-of-parser-generators] This is a list of notable lexer generators and parser generators for various language classes.
[src:peg-parser/comparison-of-parser-generators] Regular languages are a category of languages (sometimes termed Chomsky Type 3) which can be matched by a state machine (more specifically, by a deterministic finite automaton or a nondeterministic finite automaton) constructed from a regular expression.
[src:peg-parser/comparison-of-parser-generators] A classic example of a problem which a regular grammar cannot handle is the question of whether a given string contains correctly nested parentheses.
[src:peg-parser/comparison-of-parser-generators] Context-free languages are a category of languages (sometimes termed Chomsky Type 2) which can be matched by a sequence of replacement rules, each of which essentially maps each non-terminal element to a sequence of terminal elements and/or other nonterminal elements.
[src:peg-parser/comparison-of-parser-generators] Grammars of this type can match anything that can be matched by a regular grammar, and furthermore, can handle the concept of recursive "nesting" ("every A is eventually followed by a matching B"), such as the question of whether a given string contains correctly nested parentheses.
[src:peg-parser/comparison-of-parser-generators] The rules of Context-free grammars are purely local, however, and therefore cannot handle questions that require non-local analysis such as "Does a declaration exist for every variable that is used in a function?".
[src:peg-parser/comparison-of-parser-generators] To do so technically would require a more sophisticated grammar, like a Chomsky Type 1 grammar, also termed a context-sensitive grammar.
[src:peg-parser/comparison-of-parser-generators] However, parser generators for context-free grammars often support the ability for user-written code to introduce limited amounts of context-sensitivity.
[src:peg-parser/comparison-of-parser-generators] The deterministic context-free languages are a proper subset of the context-free languages which can be efficiently parsed by deterministic pushdown automata.
[src:peg-parser/comparison-of-parser-generators] This table compares parser generators with parsing expression grammars, deterministic Boolean grammars.
[src:peg-parser/comparison-of-parser-generators] This table compares parser generator languages with a general context-free grammar, a conjunctive grammar, or a Boolean grammar.
[src:peg-parser/comparison-of-parser-generators] This table compares parser generators with context-sensitive grammars.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] In formal language theory, a **context-free grammar** (**CFG**) is a formal grammar whose production rules can be applied to a nonterminal symbol regardless of its context.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] with A a *single* nonterminal symbol, and $\alpha$ a string of terminals and/or nonterminals ( $\alpha$ can be empty).
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Regardless of which symbols surround it, the single nonterminal A on the left hand side can always be replaced by $\alpha$ on the right hand side.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] This distinguishes it from a context-sensitive grammar, which can have production rules in the form $\alpha A\beta \rightarrow \alpha \gamma \beta$ with A a nonterminal symbol and $\alpha$ , $\beta$ , and $\gamma$ strings of terminal and/or nonterminal symbols.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] A formal grammar is essentially a set of production rules that describe all possible strings in a given formal language.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Production rules are simple replacements.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] replaces $\langle {\text{Stmt}}\rangle$ with ${\displaystyle \langle {\text{Id}}\rangle =\langle {\text{Expr}}\rangle$ .
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] There can be multiple replacement rules for a given nonterminal symbol.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The language generated by a grammar is the set of all strings of terminal symbols that can be derived, by repeated rule applications, from some particular nonterminal symbol ("start symbol").
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Nonterminal symbols are used during the derivation process, but do not appear in its final result string.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Languages generated by context-free grammars are known as context-free languages (CFL).
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Different context-free grammars can generate the same context-free language.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] It is important to distinguish the properties of the language (intrinsic properties) from the properties of a particular grammar (extrinsic properties).
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The language equality question (do two given context-free grammars generate the same language?) is undecidable.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Context-free grammars arise in linguistics where they are used to describe the structure of sentences and words in a natural language, and they were invented by the linguist Noam Chomsky for this purpose.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] By contrast, in computer science, as the use of recursively defined concepts increased, they were used more and more.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] In an early application, grammars are used to describe the structure of programming languages.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] In a newer application, they are used in an essential part of the Extensible Markup Language (XML) called the document type definition.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] In linguistics, some authors use the term phrase structure grammar to refer to context-free grammars, whereby phrase-structure grammars are distinct from dependency grammars.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] In computer science, a popular notation for context-free grammars is Backus–Naur form, or BNF.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Since at least the time of the ancient Indian scholar Pāṇini, linguists have described the grammars of languages in terms of their block structure, and described how sentences are recursively built up from smaller phrases, and eventually individual words or word elements.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] An essential property of these block structures is that logical units never overlap.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] John, whose blue car was in the garage, walked to the grocery store.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] A context-free grammar provides a simple and mathematically precise mechanism for describing the methods by which phrases in some natural language are built from smaller blocks, capturing the "block structure" of sentences in a natural way.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Its simplicity makes the formalism amenable to rigorous mathematical study.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Context-free grammars are a special form of semi-Thue systems that in their general form date back to the work of Axel Thue.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The formalism of context-free grammars was developed in the mid-1950s by Noam Chomsky, and also their classification as a special type of formal grammar (which he called phrase-structure grammars).
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Some authors, however, reserve the term for more restricted grammars in the Chomsky hierarchy: context-sensitive grammars or context-free grammars.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] In a broader sense, phrase structure grammars are also known as constituency grammars.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The defining trait of phrase structure grammars is thus their adherence to the constituency relation, as opposed to the dependency relation of dependency grammars.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] In Chomsky's generative grammar framework, the syntax of natural language was described by context-free rules combined with transformation rules.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Block structure was introduced into computer programming languages by the Algol project (1957–1960), which, as a consequence, also featured a context-free grammar to describe the resulting Algol syntax.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] This became a standard feature of computer languages, and the notation for grammars used in concrete descriptions of computer languages came to be known as Backus–Naur form, after two members of the Algol language design committee.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The "block structure" aspect that context-free grammars capture is so fundamental to grammar that the terms syntax and grammar are often identified with context-free grammar rules, especially in computer science.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Formal constraints not captured by the grammar are then considered to be part of the "semantics" of the language.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Context-free grammars are simple enough to allow the construction of efficient parsing algorithms that, for a given string, determine whether and how it can be generated from the grammar.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] An Earley parser is an example of such an algorithm, while the widely used LR and LL parsers are simpler algorithms that deal only with more restrictive subsets of context-free grammars.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] 2. Σ is a finite set of *terminal*s, disjoint from V, which make up the actual content of the sentence.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The set of terminals is the alphabet of the language defined by the grammar G.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] R is a finite relation in $V\times (V\cup \Sigma )^{*}$ , where the asterisk represents the Kleene star operation.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The members of R are called the *(rewrite) rule*s or *production*s of the grammar (also commonly symbolized by a P).
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] S is the start variable (or start symbol), used to represent the whole sentence (or program).
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] It is allowed for *β* to be the empty string, and in this case it is customary to denote it by ε.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The form $\alpha \rightarrow \varepsilon$ is called an ε-production.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] It is common to list all right-hand sides for the same left-hand side on the same line, using | (the vertical bar) to separate them.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Rules $\alpha \rightarrow \beta _{1}$ and $\alpha \rightarrow \beta _{2}$ can hence be written as $\alpha \rightarrow \beta _{1}\mid \beta _{2}$ .
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] In this case, $\beta _{1}$ and $\beta _{2}$ are called the first and second alternative, respectively.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Thus, v is a result of applying the rule $(\alpha ,\beta )$ to *u*.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] For any strings $u,v\in (V\cup \Sigma )^{*},$ we say u *yields* v or v is *derived* from u if there is a positive integer k and strings $u_{1},\ldots ,u_{k}\in (V\cup \Sigma )^{*}$ such that $u=u_{1}\Rightarrow u_{2}\Rightarrow \cdots \Rightarrow u_{k}=v$ .
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] This relation is denoted $u~{\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }}~v$ , or $u\Rightarrow \Rightarrow v$ in some textbooks.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] If $k\geq 2$ , the relation $u~{\stackrel {+}{\Rightarrow }}~v$ holds.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] In other words, $({\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }})$ and $({\stackrel {+}{\Rightarrow }})$ are the reflexive transitive closure (allowing a string to yield itself) and the transitive closure (requiring at least one step) of $(\Rightarrow )$ , respectively.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] of all terminal-symbol strings derivable from the start symbol.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] A language L is said to be a context-free language (CFL), if there exists a CFG G, such that $L=L(G)$ .
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Non-deterministic pushdown automata recognize exactly the context-free languages.
