[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] This language belongs instead to a more general class and can be described by a conjunctive grammar, which in turn also includes other non-context-free languages, such as the language of all words of the form a*n*b*n*c*n*.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Every regular grammar is context-free, but not all context-free grammars are regular.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The following context-free grammar, for example, is also regular.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The terminals here are a and b, while the only nonterminal is *S*.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The language described is all nonempty strings of as and bs that end in a.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] This grammar is regular: no rule has more than one nonterminal in its right-hand side, and each of these nonterminals is at the same end of the right-hand side.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Every regular grammar corresponds directly to a nondeterministic finite automaton, so we know that this is a regular language.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] A *derivation* of a string for a grammar is a sequence of grammar rule applications that transform the start symbol into the string.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] A derivation proves that the string belongs to the grammar's language.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] For clarity, the intermediate string is usually given as well.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Given such a strategy, a derivation is completely determined by the sequence of rules applied.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The distinction between leftmost derivation and rightmost derivation is important because in most parsers the transformation of the input is defined by giving a piece of code for every grammar rule that is executed whenever the rule is applied.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Therefore, it is important to know whether the parser determines a leftmost or a rightmost derivation because this determines the order in which the pieces of code will be executed.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] See for an example LL parsers and LR parsers.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] A derivation also imposes in some sense a hierarchical structure on the string that is derived.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] where {...}*S* denotes a substring recognized as belonging to *S*.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] This tree is called a *parse tree* or "concrete syntax tree" of the string, by contrast with the abstract syntax tree.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Note however that both parse trees can be obtained by both leftmost and rightmost derivations.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] If a string in the language of the grammar has more than one parsing tree, then the grammar is said to be an *ambiguous grammar*.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Such grammars are usually hard to parse because the parser cannot always decide which grammar rule it has to apply.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Usually, ambiguity is a feature of the grammar, not the language, and an unambiguous grammar can be found that generates the same context-free language.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] However, there are certain languages that can only be generated by ambiguous grammars; such languages are called *inherently ambiguous languages*.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Every context-free grammar with no ε-production has an equivalent grammar in Chomsky normal form, and a grammar in Greibach normal form.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] "Equivalent" here means that the two grammars generate the same language.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The especially simple form of production rules in Chomsky normal form grammars has both theoretical and practical implications.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] For instance, given a context-free grammar, one can use the Chomsky normal form to construct a polynomial-time algorithm that decides whether a given string is in the language represented by that grammar or not (the CYK algorithm).
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] They are not closed under general intersection (hence neither under complementation) and set difference.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The following are some decidable problems about context-free grammars.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Context-free parsing for Chomsky normal form grammars was shown by Leslie G.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Valiant to be reducible to Boolean matrix multiplication, thus inheriting its complexity upper bound of *O*(*n*2.3728639).
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Conversely, Lillian Lee has shown *O*(*n*3−*ε*) Boolean matrix multiplication to be reducible to *O*(*n*3−3*ε*) CFG parsing, thus establishing some kind of lower bound for the latter.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] A nonterminal symbol X is called *productive*, or *generating*, if there is a derivation $X~{\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }}~w$ for some string w of terminal symbols.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] X is called *reachable* if there is a derivation $S~{\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }}~\alpha X\beta$ for some strings $\alpha ,\beta$ of nonterminal and terminal symbols from the start symbol.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] X is called *useless* if it is unreachable or unproductive.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] X is called *nullable* if there is a derivation $X~{\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }}~\varepsilon$ .
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] A rule $X\rightarrow \varepsilon$ is called an *ε-production*.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] A derivation $X~{\stackrel {+}{\Rightarrow }}~X$ is called a *cycle*.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] In particular, an alternative containing a useless nonterminal symbol can be deleted from the right-hand side of a rule.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Such rules and alternatives are called *useless*.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] In the depicted example grammar, the nonterminal *D* is unreachable, and *E* is unproductive, while *C* → *C* causes a cycle.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Hence, omitting the last three rules does not change the language generated by the grammar, nor does omitting the alternatives "| *C*c | *E*e" from the right-hand side of the rule for *S*.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] A context-free grammar is said to be *proper* if it has neither useless symbols nor ε-productions nor cycles.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Combining the above algorithms, every context-free grammar not generating ε can be transformed into a weakly equivalent proper one.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] It is decidable whether a given *grammar* is a regular grammar, as well as whether it is an LL(*k*) grammar for a given *k* ≥ 0.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] If *k* is not given, the latter problem is undecidable.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Given a context-free grammar, it is not decidable whether its language is regular, nor whether it is an LL(*k*) language for a given *k*.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] There are algorithms to decide whether the language of a given context-free grammar is empty, as well as whether it is finite.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Some questions that are undecidable for wider classes of grammars become decidable for context-free grammars; e.g. the emptiness problem (whether the grammar generates any terminal strings at all), is undecidable for context-sensitive grammars, but decidable for context-free grammars.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] However, many problems are undecidable even for context-free grammars; the most prominent ones are handled in the following.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Given a CFG, does it generate the language of all strings over the alphabet of terminal symbols used in its rules?
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] A reduction can be demonstrated to this problem from the well-known undecidable problem of determining whether a Turing machine accepts a particular input (the halting problem).
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The reduction uses the concept of a *computation history*, a string describing an entire computation of a Turing machine.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] A CFG can be constructed that generates all strings that are not accepting computation histories for a particular Turing machine on a particular input, and thus it will accept all strings only if the machine does not accept that input.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Given two CFGs, do they generate the same language?
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The undecidability of this problem is a direct consequence of the previous: it is impossible to even decide whether a CFG is equivalent to the trivial CFG defining the language of all strings.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Given two CFGs, can the first one generate all strings that the second one can generate?
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] If this problem was decidable, then language equality could be decided too: two CFGs $G_{1}$ and $G_{2}$ generate the same language if $L(G_{1})$ is a subset of $L(G_{2})$ and $L(G_{2})$ is a subset of $L(G_{1})$ .
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The undecidability of this problem follows from the fact that if an algorithm to determine ambiguity existed, the Post correspondence problem could be decided, which is known to be undecidable.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Given two CFGs, is there any string derivable from both grammars?
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Then the PCP instance given by $\alpha _{1},\ldots ,\alpha _{N},\beta _{1},\ldots ,\beta _{N}$ has a solution if and only if ⁠ $L(G_{1})$ ⁠ and ⁠ $L(G_{2})$ ⁠ share a derivable string.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] The left of the string (before the b ) will represent the top of the solution for the PCP instance while the right side will be the bottom in reverse.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] An obvious way to extend the context-free grammar formalism is to allow nonterminals to have arguments, the values of which are passed along within the rules.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] This allows natural language features such as agreement and reference, and programming language analogs such as the correct use and definition of identifiers, to be expressed in a natural way.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] E.g. we can now easily express that in English sentences, the subject and verb must agree in number.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] In computer science, examples of this approach include affix grammars, attribute grammars, indexed grammars, and Van Wijngaarden two-level grammars.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Similar extensions exist in linguistics.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] An **extended context-free grammar** (or **regular right part grammar**) is one in which the right-hand side of the production rules is allowed to be a regular expression over the grammar's terminals and nonterminals.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Extended context-free grammars describe exactly the context-free languages.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Another extension is to allow additional terminal symbols to appear at the left-hand side of rules, constraining their application.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] This produces the formalism of context-sensitive grammars.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] LR parsing extends LL parsing to support a larger range of grammars; in turn, generalized LR parsing extends LR parsing to support arbitrary context-free grammars.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] On LL grammars and LR grammars, it essentially performs LL parsing and LR parsing, respectively, while on nondeterministic grammars, it is as efficient as can be expected.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Although GLR parsing was developed in the 1980s, many new language definitions and parser generators continue to be based on LL, LALR or LR parsing up to the present day.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Chomsky initially hoped to overcome the limitations of context-free grammars by adding transformation rules.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Such rules are another standard device in traditional linguistics; e.g. passivization in English.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Much of generative grammar has been devoted to finding ways of refining the descriptive mechanisms of phrase-structure grammar and transformation rules such that exactly the kinds of things can be expressed that natural language actually allows.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Allowing arbitrary transformations does not meet that goal: they are much too powerful, being Turing complete unless significant restrictions are added (e.g. no transformations that introduce and then rewrite symbols in a context-free fashion).
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Chomsky's general position regarding the non-context-freeness of natural language has held up since then, although his specific examples regarding the inadequacy of context-free grammars in terms of their weak generative capacity were later disproved.
[src:peg-parser/context-free-grammar] Gerald Gazdar and Geoffrey Pullum have argued that despite a few non-context-free constructions in natural language (such as cross-serial dependencies in Swiss German and reduplication in Bambara), the vast majority of forms in natural language are indeed context-free.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] The **Packrat parser** is a type of parser that shares similarities with the recursive descent parser in its construction.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] However, it differs because it takes parsing expression grammars (PEGs) as input rather than LL grammars.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] In 1970, Alexander Birman laid the groundwork for packrat parsing by introducing the "TMG recognition scheme" (TS), and "generalized TS" (gTS).
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] McClure's TMG compiler-compiler, and gTS was based upon Dewey Val Schorre's META compiler-compiler.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Birman's work was later refined by Aho and Ullman; and renamed as Top-Down Parsing Language (TDPL), and Generalized TDPL (GTDPL), respectively.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] These algorithms were the first of their kind to employ deterministic top-down parsing with backtracking.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Bryan Ford developed PEGs as an expansion of GTDPL and TS.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Unlike CFGs, PEGs are unambiguous and can match well with machine-oriented languages.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] PEGs, similar to GTDPL and TS, can also express all LL(k) and LR(k).
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Ford also introduced Packrat as a parser that uses memoization techniques on top of a simple PEG parser.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] This was done because PEGs have an unlimited lookahead capability resulting in a parser with exponential time performance in the worst case.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Packrat keeps track of the intermediate results for all mutually recursive parsing functions.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Each parsing function is only called once at a specific input position.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] In some instances of packrat implementation, if there is insufficient memory, certain parsing functions may need to be called multiple times at the same input position, causing the parser to take longer than linear time.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] The packrat parser takes in input the same syntax as PEGs: a simple PEG is composed of terminal and nonterminal symbols, possibly interleaved with operators that compose one or several derivation rules.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] A derivation rule is composed by a nonterminal symbol and an expression $S\rightarrow \alpha$ .
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] A special expression $\alpha _{s}$ is the starting point of the grammar.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] In case no $\alpha _{s}$ is specified, the first expression of the first rule is used.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] An input string is considered accepted by the parser if the $\alpha _{s}$ is recognized.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] As a side-effect, a string x can be recognized by the parser even if it was not fully consumed.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] An extreme case of this rule is that the grammar $S\rightarrow x*$ matches any string.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] This grammar recognizes some palindromes over the alphabet $\{a,b\}$ , with an optional digit in the middle.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Example strings accepted by the grammar include: ${\texttt {'aa'}}$ and ${\texttt {'aba3aba'}}$ .
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] But it fails to accept ${\texttt {'aaaa'}}$ .
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Left recursion happens when a grammar production refers to itself as its left-most element, either directly or indirectly.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Since Packrat is a recursive descent parser, it cannot handle left recursion directly.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] During the early stages of development, it was found that a production that is left-recursive can be transformed into a right-recursive production.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] This modification significantly simplifies the task of a Packrat parser.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Nonetheless, if there is an indirect left recursion involved, the process of rewriting can be quite complex and challenging.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] If the time complexity requirements are loosened from linear to superlinear, it is possible to modify the memoization table of a Packrat parser to permit left recursion, without altering the input grammar.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] The iterative combinators $\alpha +$ and $\alpha *$ need special attention when used in a Packrat parser: these combinators introduce a *secret* recursion that does not record intermediate results in the outcome matrix, which can lead to the parser operating with a superlinear behaviour.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] With this transformation, the intermediate results can be properly memoized.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Memoization is an optimization technique in computing that aims to speed up programs by storing the results of expensive function calls.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] This technique essentially works by caching the results so that when the same inputs occur again, the cached result is simply returned, thus avoiding the time-consuming process of re-computing.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] When using packrat parsing and memoization, it's noteworthy that the parsing function for each nonterminal is solely based on the input string.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] It does not depend on any information gathered during the parsing process.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Essentially, memoization table entries do not affect or rely on the parser's specific state at any given time.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Packrat parsing stores results in a matrix or similar data structure that allows for quick look-ups and insertions.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] When a production is encountered, the matrix is checked to see if it has already occurred.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] If it has, the result is retrieved from the matrix.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] If not, the production is evaluated, the result is inserted into the matrix, and then returned.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] When evaluating the entire $m*n$ matrix in a tabular approach, it would require $\Theta (mn)$ space.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Here, m represents the number of nonterminals, and n represents the input string size.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] In a naïve implementation, the entire table can be derived from the input string starting from the end of the string.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] The Packrat parser can be improved to update only the necessary cells in the matrix through a depth-first visit of each subexpression tree.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Consequently, using a matrix with dimensions of $m*n$ is often wasteful, as most entries would remain empty.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] These cells are linked to the input string, not to the nonterminals of the grammar.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] This means that increasing the input string size would always increase memory consumption, while the number of parsing rules changes only the worst space complexity.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Another operator called *cut* has been introduced to Packrat to reduce its average space complexity even further.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] This operator utilizes the formal structures of many programming languages to eliminate impossible derivations.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] For instance, control statements parsing in a standard programming language is mutually exclusive from the first recognized token, e.g., $\{{\mathtt {if,do,while,switch}}\}$ .
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] When a Packrat parser uses cut operators, it effectively clears its backtracking stack.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] This is because a cut operator reduces the number of possible alternatives in an ordered choice.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] By adding cut operators in the right places in a grammar's definition, the resulting Packrat parser only needs a nearly constant amount of space for memoization.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] However, the fundamental problem that packrat parsers require O(n) space has not been resolved.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Sketch of an implementation of a Packrat algorithm in a Lua-like pseudocode.
[src:peg-parser/packrat-parser] Given the following context, a free grammar that recognizes simple arithmetic expressions composed of single digits interleaved by sum, multiplication, and parenthesis.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] In computer science, a **parsing expression grammar** (**PEG**) is a type of analytic formal grammar, i.e. it describes a formal language in terms of a set of rules for recognizing strings in the language.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The formalism was introduced by Bryan Ford in 2004 and is closely related to the family of top-down parsing languages introduced in the early 1970s.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Syntactically, PEGs also look similar to context-free grammars (CFGs), but they have a different interpretation: the choice operator selects the first match in PEG, while it is ambiguous in CFG.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] This is closer to how string recognition tends to be done in practice, e.g. by a recursive descent parser.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Unlike CFGs, PEGs cannot be ambiguous; a string has exactly one valid parse tree or none.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] It is conjectured that there exist context-free languages that cannot be recognized by a PEG, but this is not yet proven.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] PEGs are well-suited to parsing computer languages (and artificial human languages such as Lojban) where multiple interpretation alternatives can be disambiguated locally, but are less likely to be useful for parsing natural languages where disambiguation may have to be global.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] A **parsing expression** is a kind of pattern that each string may either **match** or **not match**.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] In case of a match, there is a unique prefix of the string (which may be the whole string, the empty string, or something in between) which has been *consumed* by the parsing expression; this prefix is what one would usually think of as having matched the expression.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] However, whether a string matches a parsing expression *may* (because of look-ahead predicates) depend on parts of it which come after the consumed part.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] A **parsing expression language** is a set of all strings that match some specific parsing expression.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] A **parsing expression grammar** is a collection of named parsing expressions, which may reference each other.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The effect of one such reference in a parsing expression is as if the whole referenced parsing expression was given in place of the reference.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] A parsing expression grammar also has a designated **starting expression**; a string matches the grammar if it matches its starting expression.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] An element of a string matched is called a *terminal symbol*, or **terminal** for short.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Likewise the names assigned to parsing expressions are called *nonterminal symbols*, or **nonterminals** for short.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] These terms would be descriptive for generative grammars, but in the case of parsing expression grammars they are merely terminology, kept mostly because of being near ubiquitous in discussions of parsing algorithms.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Both *abstract* and *concrete* syntaxes of parsing expressions are seen in the literature, and in this article.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The abstract syntax is essentially a mathematical formula and primarily used in theoretical contexts, whereas concrete syntax parsing expressions could be used directly to control a parser.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The primary concrete syntax is that defined by Ford, although many tools have their own dialect of this.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Other tools can be closer to using a programming-language native encoding of abstract syntax parsing expressions as their concrete syntax.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The two main kinds of parsing expressions not containing another parsing expression are individual terminal symbols and nonterminal symbols.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] In the abstract syntax there is no formalised distinction, instead each symbol is supposedly defined as either terminal or nonterminal, but a common convention is to use upper case for nonterminals and lower case for terminals.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] In abstract syntax, such forms are usually formalised as nonterminals whose exact definition is elided for brevity; in Unicode, there are tens of thousands of characters that are letters.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Conversely, theoretical discussions sometimes introduce atomic abstract syntax for concepts that can alternatively be expressed using composite parsing expressions.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] In the concrete syntax, quoted and bracketed terminals have backslash escapes, so that "line feed or carriage return" may be written `[\n\r]`.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The abstract syntax counterpart of a quoted terminal of length greater than one would be the sequence of those terminals; `"bar"` is the same as `"b" "a" "r"`.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The primary concrete syntax assigns no distinct meaning to terminals depending on whether they use single or double quotes, but some dialects treat one as case-sensitive and the other as case-insensitive.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The `Identifier` is the nonterminal being defined, and the `Expression` is the parsing expression it is defined as referencing.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The `LEFTARROW` varies a bit between dialects, but is generally some left-pointing arrow or assignment symbol, such as `<-`, `←`, `:=`, or `=`.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] One way to understand it is precisely as making an assignment or definition of the nonterminal.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Another way to understand it is as a contrast to the right-pointing arrow → used in the rules of a context-free grammar; with parsing expressions the flow of information goes from expression to nonterminal, not nonterminal to expression.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] As a mathematical object, a parsing expression grammar is a tuple $(N,\Sigma ,P,e_{S})$ , where N is the set of nonterminal symbols, $\Sigma$ is the set of terminal symbols, P is a function from N to the set of parsing expressions on $N\cup \Sigma$ , and $e_{S}$ is the starting parsing expression.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Some concrete syntax dialects give the starting expression explicitly, but the primary concrete syntax instead has the implicit rule that the first nonterminal defined is the starting expression.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] However, some dialects may allow an explicit terminator, or outright require it.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] This is a PEG that recognizes mathematical formulas that apply the basic five operations to non-negative integers.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] In the above example, the terminal symbols are characters of text, represented by characters in single quotes, such as `'('` and `')'`.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The range `[0-9]` is a shortcut for the ten characters from `'0'` to `'9'`.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] (This range syntax is the same as the syntax used by regular expressions.) The nonterminal symbols are the ones that expand to other rules: *Value*, *Power*, *Product*, *Sum*, and *Expr*.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Also note that a rule like `Sum ← Sum (('+' / '-') Product)?` (with intention to achieve left-associativity) would cause infinite recursion, so it cannot be used in practice even though it can be expressed in the grammar.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The fundamental difference between context-free grammars and parsing expression grammars is that the PEG's choice operator is *ordered*.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] If the first alternative succeeds, the second alternative is ignored.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Thus ordered choice is not commutative, unlike unordered choice as in context-free grammars.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Ordered choice is analogous to soft cut operators available in some logic programming languages.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The consequence is that if a CFG is transliterated directly to a PEG, any ambiguity in the former is resolved by deterministically picking one parse tree from the possible parses.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] By carefully choosing the order in which the grammar alternatives are specified, a programmer has a great deal of control over which parse tree is selected.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Parsing expression grammars also add the and- and not- syntactic predicates.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Because they can use an arbitrarily complex sub-expression to "look ahead" into the input string without actually consuming it, they provide a powerful syntactic lookahead and disambiguation facility, in particular when reordering the alternatives cannot specify the exact parse tree desired.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Each nonterminal in a parsing expression grammar essentially represents a parsing function in a recursive descent parser, and the corresponding parsing expression represents the "code" comprising the function.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] An atomic parsing expression consisting of a single **terminal** (i.e. literal) succeeds if the first character of the input string matches that terminal, and in that case consumes the input character; otherwise the expression yields a failure result.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] An atomic parsing expression consisting of the **empty** string always trivially succeeds without consuming any input.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] An atomic parsing expression consisting of a **nonterminal** *A* represents a recursive call to the nonterminal-function *A*.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] A nonterminal may succeed without actually consuming any input, and this is considered an outcome distinct from failure.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The **sequence** operator *e*1 *e*2 first invokes *e*1, and if *e*1 succeeds, subsequently invokes *e*2 on the remainder of the input string left unconsumed by *e*1, and returns the result.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] If either *e*1 or *e*2 fails, then the sequence expression *e*1 *e*2 fails (consuming no input).
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The **choice** operator *e*1 / *e*2 first invokes *e*1, and if *e*1 succeeds, returns its result immediately.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Otherwise, if *e*1 fails, then the choice operator backtracks to the original input position at which it invoked *e*1, but then calls *e*2 instead, returning *e*2's result.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The **zero-or-more**, **one-or-more**, and **optional** operators consume zero or more, one or more, or zero or one consecutive repetitions of their sub-expression *e*, respectively.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Unlike in context-free grammars and regular expressions, however, these operators *always* behave greedily, consuming as much input as possible and never backtracking.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The **and-predicate** expression &*e* invokes the sub-expression *e*, and then succeeds if *e* succeeds and fails if *e* fails, but in either case *never consumes any input*.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The **not-predicate** expression !*e* succeeds if *e* fails and fails if *e* succeeds, again consuming no input in either case.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The following recursive rule matches standard C-style if/then/else statements in such a way that the optional "else" clause always binds to the innermost "if", because of the implicit prioritization of the '/' operator.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The following recursive rule matches Pascal-style nested comment syntax, `(* which can (* nest *) like this *)`.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Recall that `.` matches any single character.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The parsing expression `foo &(bar)` matches and consumes the text "foo" but only if it is followed by the text "bar".
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The parsing expression `foo !(bar)` matches the text "foo" but only if it is *not* followed by the text "bar".
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The expression `!(a+ b) a` matches a single "a" but only if it is not part of an arbitrarily long sequence of a's followed by a b.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The parsing expression `('a'/'b')*` matches and consumes an arbitrary-length sequence of a 's and b 's.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The production rule `S ← ('a' S 'b')?` matches the simple context-free language $\{a^{n}b^{n}:n\geq 0\}$ .
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Any parsing expression grammar can be converted directly into a recursive descent parser.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Due to the unlimited lookahead capability that the grammar formalism provides, however, the resulting parser could exhibit exponential time performance in the worst case.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] It is possible to obtain better performance for any parsing expression grammar by converting its recursive descent parser into a *packrat parser*, which always runs in linear time, at the cost of substantially greater storage space requirements.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Because of this memoization, a packrat parser has the ability to parse many context-free grammars and *any* parsing expression grammar (including some that do not represent context-free languages) in linear time.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Examples of memoized recursive descent parsers are known from at least as early as 1993.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] It is also possible to build LL parsers and LR parsers from parsing expression grammars, with better worst-case performance than a recursive descent parser without memoization, but the unlimited lookahead capability of the grammar formalism is then lost.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Therefore, not all languages that can be expressed using parsing expression grammars can be parsed by LL or LR parsers.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] A pika parser uses dynamic programming to apply PEG rules bottom-up and right to left, which is the inverse of the normal recursive descent order of top-down, left to right.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Many parsing algorithms require a preprocessing step where the grammar is first compiled into an opaque executable form, often some sort of automaton.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Parsing expressions can be executed directly (even if it is typically still advisable to transform the human-readable PEGs shown in this article into a more native format, such as S-expressions, before evaluating them).
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Compared to pure regular expressions (i.e., describing a language recognisable using a finite automaton), PEGs are vastly more powerful.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Here `AB !.` is the starting expression.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The `!.` part enforces that the input ends after the `AB`, by saying “there is no next character”; unlike regular expressions, which have magic constraints `$` or `\Z` for this, parsing expressions can express the end of input using only the basic primitives.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The `*`, `+`, and `?` of parsing expressions are similar to those in regular expressions, but a difference is that these operate strictly in a greedy mode.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] This is ultimately due to `/` being an ordered choice.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] is both a valid regular expression and a valid parsing expression.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] As regular expression, it matches `bc`, but as parsing expression it does not match, because the `[ab]?` will match the `b`, then `[bc]` will match the `c`, leaving nothing for the `[cd]`, so at that point matching the sequence fails.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] "Trying again" with having `[ab]?` match the empty string is explicitly against the semantics of parsing expressions; this is not an edge case of a particular matching algorithm, instead it is the sought behaviour.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] is effectively saying "from state A transition to state B or C if the next character is x, or to state D if the next character is y".
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] It would not make use of the parsing expression variants of the repetition operations.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] For accepting states of the NFA, the definition of the nonterminal should be surrounded by `?`.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Concerning the entry states of the NFA, they should all be listed, separated by `/`, in the definition of the starting non-terminal.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Note that while it's possible to transform a regular expression into a *deterministic* finite automaton (DFA for short) instead of an NFA, this should be *avoided* because the DFA equivalent of a regular expression can be exponentially larger.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] In fact, there is a sequence of regular expressions for which all of the DFA equivalents are exponentially larger.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] PEGs can comfortably be given in terms of characters, whereas context-free grammars (CFGs) are usually given in terms of tokens, thus requiring an extra step of tokenisation in front of parsing proper.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] An advantage of not having a separate tokeniser is that different parts of the language (for example embedded mini-languages) can easily have different tokenisation rules.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] In the strict formal sense, PEGs are likely incomparable to CFGs, but practically there are many things that PEGs can do which pure CFGs cannot, whereas it is difficult to come up with examples of the contrary.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] In particular PEGs can be crafted to natively resolve ambiguities, such as the "dangling else" problem in C, C++, and Java, whereas CFG-based parsing often needs a rule outside of the grammar to resolve them.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Moreover any PEG can be parsed in linear time by using a packrat parser, as described above, whereas parsing according to a general CFG is asymptotically equivalent to boolean matrix multiplication (thus likely between quadratic and cubic time).
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] One classical example of a formal language which is provably not context-free is the language $\{a^{n}b^{n}c^{n}:n\geq 0\}$ : an arbitrary number of a 's are followed by an equal number of b 's, which in turn are followed by an equal number of c 's.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] For `A` to match, the first stretch of a 's must be followed by exactly the same number of b 's and no more, and in addition `B` has to match where the a 's switch to b 's, which means those b 's are followed by an equal number of c 's.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] PEG parsing is typically carried out via *packrat parsing*, which uses memoization to eliminate redundant parsing steps.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Packrat parsing requires internal storage proportional to the total input size, rather than to the depth of the parse tree as with LR parsers.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Whether this is a significant difference depends on circumstances; if parsing is a service provided as a function then the parser will have stored the full parse tree up until returning it, and already that parse tree will typically be of size proportional to the total input size.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] If parsing is instead provided as a generator then one might get away with only keeping parts of the parse tree in memory, but the feasibility of this depends on the grammar.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] A parsing expression grammar can be designed so that only after consuming the full input will the parser discover that it needs to backtrack to the beginning, which again could require storage proportional to total input size.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] For recursive grammars and some inputs, the depth of the parse tree can be proportional to the input size, so both an LR parser and a packrat parser will appear to have the same worst-case asymptotic performance.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] However in many domains, for example hand-written source code, the expression nesting depth has an effectively constant bound quite independent of the length of the program, because expressions nested beyond a certain depth tend to get refactored.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] When it is not necessary to keep the full parse tree, a more accurate analysis would take the depth of the parse tree into account separately from the input size.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] In order to attain linear overall complexity, the storage used for memoization must furthermore provide amortized constant time access to individual data items memoized.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] In practice that is no problem — for example a dynamically sized hash table attains this – but that makes use of pointer arithmetic, so it presumes having a random-access machine.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Theoretical discussions of data structures and algorithms have an unspoken tendency to presume a more restricted model (possibly that of lambda calculus, possibly that of Scheme), where a sparse table rather has to be built using trees, and data item access is not constant time.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Traditional parsing algorithms such as the LL parser are not affected by this, but it becomes a penalty for the reputation of packrat parsers: they rely on operations of seemingly ill repute.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Viewed the other way around, this says packrat parsers tap into computational power readily available in real life systems, that older parsing algorithms do not understand to employ.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] A PEG is called *well-formed* if it contains no *left-recursive* rules, i.e., rules that allow a nonterminal to expand to an expression in which the same nonterminal occurs as the leftmost symbol.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] For a left-to-right top-down parser, such rules cause infinite regress: parsing will continually expand the same nonterminal without moving forward in the string.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Therefore, to allow packrat parsing, left recursion must be eliminated.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] A difference lies in the abstract syntax trees generated: with recursion each `Sum` or `Args` can have at most two children, but with repetition there can be arbitrarily many.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] If later stages of processing require that such lists of children are recast as trees with bounded degree, for example microprocessor instructions for addition typically only allow two operands, then properties such as left-associativity would be imposed after the PEG-directed parsing stage.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Therefore left-recursion is practically less likely to trouble a PEG packrat parser than, say, an LL(k) context-free parser, unless one insists on using context-free idioms.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] However, not all cases of recursion are about repetition.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Unfortunately matching an `Expr` requires testing if a `Sum` matches, while matching a `Sum` requires testing if an `Expr` matches.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Because the term appears in the leftmost position, these rules make up a circular definition that cannot be resolved.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] (Circular definitions that can be resolved exist—such as in the original formulation from the first example—but such definitions are required not to exhibit pathological recursion.) However, left-recursive rules can always be rewritten to eliminate left-recursion.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The process of rewriting *indirectly* left-recursive rules is complex in some packrat parsers, especially when semantic actions are involved.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] With some modification, traditional packrat parsing can support direct left recursion, but doing so results in a loss of the linear-time parsing property which is generally the justification for using PEGs and packrat parsing in the first place.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Only the OMeta parsing algorithm supports full direct and indirect left recursion without additional attendant complexity (but again, at a loss of the linear time complexity), whereas all GLR parsers support left recursion.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] A common first impression of PEGs is that they look like CFGs with certain convenience features — repetition operators `*+?` as in regular expressions and lookahead predicates `&!` — plus ordered choice for disambiguation.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] This understanding can be sufficient when one's goal is to create a parser for a language, but it is not sufficient for more theoretical discussions of the computational power of parsing expressions.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] In particular the nondeterminism inherent in the unordered choice `|` of context-free grammars makes it very different from the deterministic ordered choice `/`.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Neither LL(k) nor LR(k) parsing algorithms are capable of recognizing this example.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] However, this grammar can be used by a general CFG parser like the CYK algorithm.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] However, the *language* in question can be recognised by all these types of parser, since it is in fact a regular language (that of strings of an odd number of x's).
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] As expected, it recursively tries to match the nonterminal `S` at increasing positions in this string, until failing the match against the `q`, and after that begins to backtrack.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Matching against a parsing expression is greedy, in the sense that the first success encountered is the only one considered.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Even if locally the choices are ordered longest first, there is no guarantee that this greedy matching will find the globally longest match.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] LL(k) and LR(k) parser generators will fail to complete when the input grammar is ambiguous.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] This is a feature in the common case that the grammar is intended to be unambiguous but is defective.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] A PEG parser generator will resolve unintended ambiguities earliest-match-first, which may be arbitrary and lead to surprising parses.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The ordering of productions in a PEG grammar affects not only the resolution of ambiguity, but also the *language matched*.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Ford notes that *The second alternative in the latter PEG rule will never succeed because the first choice is always taken if the input string ... begins with 'a'.*.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Thus, adding a new option to a PEG grammar can *remove* strings from the language matched, e.g. ⁠ $G_{2}$ ⁠ is the addition of a rule to the single-production grammar `A = "a" "b"`, which contains a string not matched by ⁠ $G_{2}$ ⁠.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Furthermore, constructing a grammar to match ⁠ $L(G_{1})\cup L(G_{2})$ ⁠ from PEG grammars ⁠ $G_{1}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $G_{2}$ ⁠ is not always a trivial task.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] It is an open problem to give a concrete example of a context-free language which cannot be recognized by a parsing expression grammar.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] In particular, it is open whether a parsing expression grammar can recognize the language of palindromes.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] The class of parsing expression languages is closed under set intersection and complement, thus also under set union.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] In stark contrast to the case for context-free grammars, it is not possible to generate elements of a parsing expression language from its grammar.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Furthermore, it is algorithmically undecidable whether the language recognized by a parsing expression grammar is empty.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] One reason for this is that any instance of the Post correspondence problem reduces to an instance of the problem of deciding whether a parsing expression language is empty.
[src:peg-parser/parsing-expression-grammar] Recall that an instance of the Post correspondence problem consists of a list $(\alpha _{1},\beta _{1}),(\alpha _{2},\beta _{2}),\dotsc ,(\alpha _{n},\beta _{n})$ of pairs of strings (of terminal symbols).
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In computer science, **recursion** is a method of solving a computational problem where the solution depends on solutions to smaller instances of the same problem.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Recursion solves such recursive problems by using functions that call themselves from within their own code.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The approach can be applied to many types of problems, and recursion is one of the central ideas of computer science.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Most computer programming languages support recursion by allowing a function to call itself from within its own code.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Some functional programming languages (for instance, Clojure) do not define any built-in looping constructs, and instead rely solely on recursion.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] It is proved in computability theory that these recursion-only languages are Turing complete; this means that they are as powerful (they can be used to solve the same problems) as imperative languages based on control structures such as `while` and `for`.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Repeatedly calling a function from within itself may cause the call stack to have a size equal to the sum of the input sizes of all involved calls.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] It follows that, for problems that can be solved easily by iteration, recursion is generally less efficient, and, for certain problems, algorithmic or compiler-optimization techniques such as tail call optimization may improve computational performance over a naive recursive implementation.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The development of recursion in computer science grew out of mathematical logic and later became an essential part of programming language design.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The early work done by Church, Gödel, Kleene, and Turing on recursive function and computability laid the groundwork that made recursion possible in programming languages.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Recursion has been used by mathematicians for a long time, but it only became a practical tool for programming in the late 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Key figures such as John McCarthy and the ALGOL 60 design committee contributed to introducing recursion into programming.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] John McCarthy took the first steps by creating the programming language LISP in 1960.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In his paper *Recursive Functions of Symbolic Expressions and Their Computation by Machine, Part I*, McCarthy showed that recursion could be core in a programming language that works with symbols by processing them step by step.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In LISP, recursion could be used in functions using simple rules, and there was also a way to evaluate them in the language.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] This demonstrated that recursion was a practical way to write programs and that it also describes the process of computation.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Therefore, LISP became one of the first programming languages to use recursion as a main feature, and later on also influenced other languages that followed.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] During that time, recursion was also added to ALGOL 60.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The *Report on the Algorithmic Language ALGOL 60*, which was published in 1960, was the outcome of an international attempt at designing a standard language.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Allowing procedures to call themselves was one of the new important features of the language.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Before that, only loops were allowed to be used by programmers, so it was a significant change.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Recursion allowed programmers to describe algorithms in a more natural and flexible way.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The definition of a recursive function is typically divided into two parts: one or more base case(s) and one or more recursive case(s).
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] This structure mirrors the logic of mathematical induction, which is a proof technique where proving the base case(s) and the inductive step ensures that a given theorem holds for all valid inputs.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The base case specifies input values for which the function can provide a result directly, without any further recursion.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] These are typically the simplest or smallest possible inputs (which can be solved trivially), allowing a computation to terminate.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Base cases are essential because they prevent infinite regress.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In other words, they define a stopping condition that terminates the recursion.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] An example is computing the factorial of an integer n, which is the product of all integers from 0 to n.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] For this problem, the definition 0! = 1 is a base case.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Without it, the recursion may continue indefinitely, leading to non-termination or even stack overflow errors in actual implementations.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Designing a correct base case is crucial for both theoretical and practical reasons.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Some problems have a natural base case (e.g., the empty list is a base case in some recursive list-processing functions), while others require an additional parameter to provide a stopping criterion (e.g., using a depth counter in recursive tree traversal).
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In recursive computer programming, omitting the base case or defining it incorrectly may result in unintended infinite recursion.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In a study, researchers showed that many students struggle to identify appropriate base cases.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The recursive case describes how to break down a problem into smaller sub-problems of the same form.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Each recursive step transforms the input so that it approaches a base case, ensuring progress toward termination.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] If the reduction step fails to progress toward a base case, the algorithm can get trapped in an infinite loop.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In the factorial example, the recursive case is defined as: $n!=n\cdot (n-1)!\,,\forall n>0.$ Here, each invocation of the function decreases the input n by 1.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Thus, it ensures that the recursion eventually reaches the base case of $n=0$ .
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The recursive case is analogous to the inductive step in a proof by induction: it assumes that the function works for a smaller instance and then extends this assumption to the current input.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Recursive definitions and algorithms thus closely parallel inductive arguments in mathematics, and their correctness often relies on similar reasoning techniques.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] There are several practical applications of recursion that follow the base case and recursive case structure.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] These are widely used to solve complex problems in computer science.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Many computer programs must process or generate an arbitrarily large quantity of data.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Recursion is a technique for representing data whose exact size is unknown to the programmer: the programmer can specify this data with a self-referential definition.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] There are two types of self-referential definitions: inductive and coinductive definitions.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] An inductively defined recursive data definition is one that specifies how to construct instances of the data.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The code above specifies a list of strings to be either empty, or a structure that contains a string and a list of strings.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The self-reference in the definition permits the construction of lists of any (finite) number of strings.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Similarly recursive definitions are often used to model the structure of expressions and statements in programming languages.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] This says that an expression is either a number, a product of two expressions, or a sum of two expressions.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] By recursively referring to expressions in the second and third lines, the grammar permits arbitrarily complicated arithmetic expressions such as `(5 * ((3 * 6) + 8))`, with more than one product or sum operation in a single expression.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] A coinductive data definition is one that specifies the operations that may be performed on a piece of data; typically, self-referential coinductive definitions are used for data structures of infinite size.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Corecursion is related to coinduction, and can be used to compute particular instances of (possibly) infinite objects.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] As a programming technique, it is used most often in the context of lazy programming languages, and can be preferable to recursion when the desired size or precision of a program's output is unknown.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In such cases the program requires both a definition for an infinitely large (or infinitely precise) result, and a mechanism for taking a finite portion of that result.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The problem of computing the first n prime numbers is one that can be solved with a corecursive program (e.g. here).
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Recursion that contains only a single self-reference is known as **single recursion**, while recursion that contains multiple self-references is known as **multiple recursion**.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Standard examples of single recursion include list traversal, such as in a linear search, or computing the factorial function, while standard examples of multiple recursion include tree traversal, such as in a depth-first search.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Single recursion is often much more efficient than multiple recursion, and can generally be replaced by an iterative computation, running in linear time and requiring constant space.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Multiple recursion, by contrast, may require exponential time and space, and is more fundamentally recursive, not being able to be replaced by iteration without an explicit stack.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Multiple recursion can sometimes be converted to single recursion (and, if desired, thence to iteration).
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] For example, while computing the Fibonacci sequence naively entails multiple iteration, as each value requires two previous values, it can be computed by single recursion by passing two successive values as parameters.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Most basic examples of recursion, and most of the examples presented here, demonstrate ***direct* recursion**, in which a function calls itself.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] *Indirect* recursion occurs when a function is called not by itself but by another function that it called (either directly or indirectly).
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] For example, if *f* calls *f,* that is direct recursion, but if *f* calls *g* which calls *f,* then that is indirect recursion of *f.* Chains of three or more functions are possible; for example, function 1 calls function 2, function 2 calls function 3, and function 3 calls function 1 again.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Indirect recursion is also called mutual recursion, which is a more symmetric term, though this is simply a difference of emphasis, not a different notion.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Similarly a set of three or more functions that call each other can be called a set of mutually recursive functions.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Recursion is usually done by explicitly calling a function by name.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] However, recursion can also be done via implicitly calling a function based on the current context, which is particularly useful for anonymous functions, and is known as anonymous recursion.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Some authors classify recursion as either "structural" or "generative".
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Thus, the defining characteristic of a structurally recursive function is that the argument to each recursive call is the content of a field of the original input.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Structural recursion includes nearly all tree traversals, including XML processing, binary tree creation and search, etc.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] By considering the algebraic structure of the natural numbers (that is, a natural number is either zero or the successor of a natural number), functions such as factorial may also be regarded as structural recursion.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] This distinction is important in proving termination of a function.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In actual implementation, rather than a pure recursive function (single check for base case, otherwise recursive step), a number of modifications may be made, for purposes of clarity or efficiency.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] On the basis of elegance, wrapper functions are generally approved, while short-circuiting the base case is frowned upon, particularly in academia.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Hybrid algorithms are often used for efficiency, to reduce the overhead of recursion in small cases, and arm's-length recursion is a special case of this.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] A wrapper function is a function that is directly called but does not recurse itself, instead calling a separate auxiliary function which actually does the recursion.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In languages that support nested functions, the auxiliary function can be nested inside the wrapper function and use a shared scope.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In the absence of nested functions, auxiliary functions are instead a separate function, if possible private (as they are not called directly), and information is shared with the wrapper function by using pass-by-reference.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Short-circuiting the base case, also known as **arm's-length recursion**, consists of checking the base case *before* making a recursive call – i.e., checking if the next call will be the base case, instead of calling and then checking for the base case.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Short-circuiting is particularly done for efficiency reasons, to avoid the overhead of a function call that immediately returns.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Note that since the base case has already been checked for (immediately before the recursive step), it does not need to be checked for separately, but one does need to use a wrapper function for the case when the overall recursion starts with the base case itself.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] For example, in the factorial function, properly the base case is 0! = 1, while immediately returning 1 for 1! is a short circuit, and may miss 0; this can be mitigated by a wrapper function.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The box shows C code to shortcut factorial cases 0 and 1.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Short-circuiting is primarily a concern when many base cases are encountered, such as Null pointers in a tree, which can be linear in the number of function calls, hence significant savings for *O*(*n*) algorithms; this is illustrated below for a depth-first search.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Short-circuiting on a tree corresponds to considering a leaf (non-empty node with no children) as the base case, rather than considering an empty node as the base case.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] If there is only a single base case, such as in computing the factorial, short-circuiting provides only *O*(1) savings.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Because short-circuiting has a more complicated flow, compared with the clear separation of base case and recursive step in standard recursion, it is often considered poor style, particularly in academia.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] A basic example of short-circuiting is given in depth-first search (DFS) of a binary tree; see binary trees section for standard recursive discussion.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In terms of the standard steps, this moves the base case check *before* the recursive step.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Alternatively, these can be considered a different form of base case and recursive step, respectively.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Note that this requires a wrapper function to handle the case when the tree itself is empty (root node is Null).
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In the case of a perfect binary tree of height *h,* there are 2*h*+1−1 nodes and 2*h*+1 Null pointers as children (2 for each of the 2*h* leaves), so short-circuiting cuts the number of function calls in half in the worst case.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Note the use of short-circuit evaluation of the Boolean && (AND) operators, so that the recursive call is made only if the node is valid (non-Null).
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Note that while the first term in the AND is a pointer to a node, the second term is a Boolean, so the overall expression evaluates to a Boolean.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] This is a common idiom in recursive short-circuiting.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] This is in addition to the short-circuit evaluation of the Boolean || (OR) operator, to only check the right child if the left child fails.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In fact, the entire control flow of these functions can be replaced with a single Boolean expression in a return statement, but legibility suffers at no benefit to efficiency.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Recursive algorithms are often inefficient for small data, due to the overhead of repeated function calls and returns.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] For this reason efficient implementations of recursive algorithms often start with the recursive algorithm, but then switch to a different algorithm when the input becomes small.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] An important example is merge sort, which is often implemented by switching to the non-recursive insertion sort when the data is sufficiently small, as in the tiled merge sort.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Hybrid recursive algorithms can often be further refined, as in Timsort, derived from a hybrid merge sort/insertion sort.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Recursion and iteration are equally expressive: recursion can be replaced by iteration with an explicit call stack, while iteration can be replaced with tail recursion.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Which approach is preferable depends on the problem under consideration and the language used.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In imperative programming, iteration is preferred, particularly for simple recursion, as it avoids the overhead of function calls and call stack management, but recursion is generally used for multiple recursion.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] By contrast, in functional languages recursion is preferred, with tail recursion optimization leading to little overhead.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Implementing an algorithm using iteration may not be easily achievable.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] For an imperative language the overhead is to define the function, and for a functional language the overhead is to define the accumulator variable x.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Most programming languages in use today allow the direct specification of recursive functions and procedures.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] When such a function is called, the program's runtime environment keeps track of the various instances of the function (often using a call stack, although other methods may be used).
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Every recursive function can be transformed into an iterative function by replacing recursive calls with iterative control constructs and simulating the call stack with a stack explicitly managed by the program.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Conversely, all iterative functions and procedures that can be evaluated by a computer (see Turing completeness) can be expressed in terms of recursive functions; iterative control constructs such as while loops and for loops are routinely rewritten in recursive form in functional languages.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] However, in practice this rewriting depends on tail call elimination, which is not a feature of all languages.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] As a concrete example, the difference in performance between recursive and iterative implementations of the "factorial" example above depends highly on the compiler used.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In languages where looping constructs are preferred, the iterative version may be as much as several orders of magnitude faster than the recursive one.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In functional languages, the overall time difference of the two implementations may be negligible; in fact, the cost of multiplying the larger numbers first rather than the smaller numbers (which the iterative version given here happens to do) may overwhelm any time saved by choosing iteration.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In some programming languages, the maximum size of the call stack is much less than the space available in the heap, and recursive algorithms tend to require more stack space than iterative algorithms.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Consequently, these languages sometimes place a limit on the depth of recursion to avoid stack overflows; Python is one such language.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Note the caveat below regarding the special case of tail recursion.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Because recursive algorithms can be subject to stack overflows, they may be vulnerable to pathological or malicious input.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Some malware specifically targets a program's call stack and takes advantage of the stack's inherently recursive nature.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Even in the absence of malware, a stack overflow caused by unbounded recursion can be fatal to the program, and exception handling logic may not prevent the corresponding process from being terminated.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Multiply recursive problems are inherently recursive, because of prior state they need to track.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] One example is tree traversal as in depth-first search; though both recursive and iterative methods are used, they contrast with list traversal and linear search in a list, which is a singly recursive and thus naturally iterative method.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Other examples include divide-and-conquer algorithms such as Quicksort, and functions such as the Ackermann function.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] All of these algorithms can be implemented iteratively with the help of an explicit stack, but the programmer effort involved in managing the stack, and the complexity of the resulting program, arguably outweigh any advantages of the iterative solution.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Recursive algorithms can be replaced with non-recursive counterparts.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] One method for replacing recursive algorithms is to simulate them using heap memory in place of stack memory.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] An alternative is to develop a replacement algorithm entirely based on non-recursive methods, which can be challenging.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] For example, recursive algorithms for matching wildcards, such as Rich Salz' wildmat algorithm, were once typical.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Non-recursive algorithms for the same purpose, such as the Krauss matching wildcards algorithm, have been developed to avoid the drawbacks of recursion and have improved only gradually based on techniques such as collecting tests and profiling performance.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Tail-recursive functions are functions in which all recursive calls are tail calls and hence do not build up any deferred operations.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] For example, the gcd function (shown again below) is tail-recursive.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In contrast, the factorial function (also below) is **not** tail-recursive; because its recursive call is not in tail position, it builds up deferred multiplication operations that must be performed after the final recursive call completes.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] With a compiler or interpreter that treats tail-recursive calls as jumps rather than function calls, a tail-recursive function such as gcd will execute using constant space.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Thus the program is essentially iterative, equivalent to using imperative language control structures like the "for" and "while" loops.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The significance of tail recursion is that when making a tail-recursive call (or any tail call), the caller's return position need not be saved on the call stack; when the recursive call returns, it will branch directly on the previously saved return position.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Therefore, in languages that recognize this property of tail calls, tail recursion saves both space and time.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The output of function 2 is that of function 1 with the lines swapped.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In the case of a function calling itself only once, instructions placed before the recursive call are executed once per recursion before any of the instructions placed after the recursive call.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The latter are executed repeatedly after the maximum recursion has been reached.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Also note that the *order* of the print statements is reversed, which is due to the way the functions and statements are stored on the call stack.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The definition above translates straightforwardly to functional programming languages such as Scheme; this is an example of iteration implemented recursively.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The Euclidean algorithm, which computes the greatest common divisor of two integers, can be written recursively.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The recursive program above is tail-recursive; it is equivalent to an iterative algorithm, and the computation shown above shows the steps of evaluation that would be performed by a language that eliminates tail calls.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Below is a version of the same algorithm using explicit iteration, suitable for a language that does not eliminate tail calls.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] By maintaining its state entirely in the variables *x* and *y* and using a looping construct, the program avoids making recursive calls and growing the call stack.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The iterative algorithm requires a temporary variable, and even given knowledge of the Euclidean algorithm it is more difficult to understand the process by simple inspection, although the two algorithms are very similar in their steps.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The Towers of Hanoi is a mathematical puzzle whose solution illustrates recursion.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] There are three pegs which can hold stacks of disks of different diameters.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] A larger disk may never be stacked on top of a smaller.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Starting with *n* disks on one peg, they must be moved to another peg one at a time.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] What is the smallest number of steps to move the stack?
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Although not all recursive functions have an explicit solution, the Tower of Hanoi sequence can be reduced to an explicit formula.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The binary search algorithm is a method of searching a sorted array for a single element by cutting the array in half with each recursive pass.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Recursion is used in this algorithm because with each pass a new array is created by cutting the old one in half.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The binary search procedure is then called recursively, this time on the new (and smaller) array.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Typically the array's size is adjusted by manipulating a beginning and ending index.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The algorithm exhibits a logarithmic order of growth because it essentially divides the problem domain in half with each pass.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] An important application of recursion in computer science is in defining dynamic data structures such as lists and trees.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Recursive data structures can dynamically grow to a theoretically infinite size in response to runtime requirements; in contrast, the size of a static array must be set at compile time.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The examples in this section illustrate what is known as "structural recursion".
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] This term refers to the fact that the recursive procedures are acting on data that is defined recursively.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Below is a C definition of a linked list node structure.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Notice especially how the node is defined in terms of itself.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The "next" element of `LinkedList` is a pointer to another linked list, effectively creating a list type.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Because the *struct node* data structure is defined recursively, procedures that operate on it can be implemented naturally as recursive procedures.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The *list_print* procedure defined below walks down the list until the list is empty (i.e., the list pointer has a value of NULL).
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] For each node it prints the data element (an integer).
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] In the C implementation, the list remains unchanged by the *list_print* procedure.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Below is a simple definition for a binary tree node.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Like the node for linked lists, it is defined in terms of itself, recursively.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] There are two self-referential pointers: left (pointing to the left sub-tree) and right (pointing to the right sub-tree).
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Operations on the tree can be implemented using recursion.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] At most two recursive calls will be made for any given call to *tree_contains* as defined above.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The above example illustrates an in-order traversal of the binary tree.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] A Binary search tree is a special case of the binary tree where the data elements of each node are in order.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Since the number of files in a filesystem may vary, recursion is the only practical way to traverse and thus enumerate its contents.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] Traversing a filesystem is very similar to that of tree traversal, therefore the concepts behind tree traversal are applicable to traversing a filesystem.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] More specifically, the code below would be an example of a preorder traversal of a filesystem.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] This code is both recursion and iteration - the files and directories are iterated, and each directory is opened recursively.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The "rtraverse" method is an example of direct recursion, whilst the "traverse" method is a wrapper function.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The "base case" scenario is that there will always be a fixed number of files and/or directories in a given filesystem.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] The time efficiency of recursive algorithms can be expressed in a recurrence relation of Big O notation.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p01] They can (usually) then be simplified into a single Big-O term.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] In the procedural interpretation of logic programs, clauses (or rules) of the form `A :- B` are treated as procedures, which reduce goals of the form `A` to subgoals of the form `B`.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] define a procedure, which can be used to search for a path from *X* to *Y*, either by finding a direct arc from *X* to *Y*, or by finding an arc from *X* to *Z*, and then searching recursively for a path from *Z* to *Y*.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] Prolog executes the procedure by reasoning top-down (or backwards) and searching the space of possible paths depth-first, one branch at a time.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] If it tries the second clause, and finitely fails to find a path from *Z* to *Y*, it backtracks and tries to find an arc from *X* to another node, and then searches for a path from that other node to *Y*.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] However, in the logical reading of logic programs, clauses are understood declaratively as universally quantified conditionals.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] For example, the recursive clause of the path-finding procedure is understood as representing the knowledge that, for every *X*, *Y* and *Z*, if there is an arc from *X* to *Z* and a path from *Z* to *Y* then there is a path from *X* to *Y*.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] The logical reading frees the reader from needing to know how the clause is used to solve problems.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] The clause can be used top-down, as in Prolog, to reduce problems to subproblems.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] Or it can be used bottom-up (or forwards), as in Datalog, to derive conclusions from conditions.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] This separation of concerns is a form of abstraction, which separates declarative knowledge from problem solving methods (see Algorithm#Algorithm = Logic + Control).
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] A common mistake among programmers is not providing a way to exit a recursive function, often by omitting or incorrectly checking the base case, letting it run (at least theoretically) infinitely by endlessly calling itself recursively.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] This is called *infinite recursion*, and the program will never terminate.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] In practice, this typically exhausts the available stack space.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] In most programming environments, a program with infinite recursion will not really run forever.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] Eventually, something will break and the program will report an error.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] However, if tail call optimization is used then the recursive calls may be optimized into an infinite loop that can run forever.
[src:peg-parser/recursion-computer-science-p02] Running this code will result in a stack overflow error.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] A TDPL grammar can be viewed as an extremely minimalistic formal representation of a recursive descent parser, in which each of the nonterminals schematically represents a parsing function.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] Note that a nonterminal-function may succeed without actually consuming any input, and this is considered an outcome distinct from failure.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] A nonterminal *A* defined by a rule of the form *A* → ε always succeeds without consuming any input, regardless of the input string provided.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] Conversely, a rule of the form *A* → *f* always fails regardless of input.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] A rule of the form *A* → *a* succeeds if the next character in the input string is the terminal *a*, in which case the nonterminal succeeds and consumes that one terminal; if the next input character does not match (or there is no next character), then the nonterminal fails.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] A nonterminal *A* defined by a rule of the form *A* → *BC/D* first recursively invokes nonterminal *B*, and if *B* succeeds, invokes *C* on the remainder of the input string left unconsumed by *B*.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] If both *B* and *C* succeed, then *A* in turn succeeds and consumes the same total number of input characters that *B* and *C* together did.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] If either *B* or *C* fails, however, then *A* backtracks to the original point in the input string where it was first invoked, and then invokes *D* on that original input string, returning whatever result *D* produces.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] The above examples can be represented equivalently but much more succinctly in parsing expression grammar notation as `S ← (a/b)*` and `S ← ({S})*`, respectively.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] A slight variation of TDPL, known as **Generalized TDPL** or GTDPL, greatly increases the apparent expressiveness of TDPL while retaining the same minimalist approach (though they are actually equivalent).
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] In GTDPL, instead of TDPL's recursive rule form *A* → *BC/D*, the rule form *A* → *B[C,D]* is used.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] This rule is interpreted as follows: When nonterminal *A* is invoked on some input string, it first recursively invokes *B*.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] If *B* succeeds, then *A* subsequently invokes *C* on the remainder of the input left unconsumed by *B*, and returns the result of *C* to the original caller.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] If *B* fails, on the other hand, then *A* invokes *D* on the original input string, and passes the result back to the caller.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] The important difference between this rule form and the *A* → *BC/D* rule form used in TDPL is that *C* and *D* are never *both* invoked in the same call to *A*: that is, the GTDPL rule acts more like a "pure" if/then/else construct using *B* as the condition.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] In GTDPL it is straightforward to express interesting non-context-free languages such as the classic example {a*n*b*n*c*n*}.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] A GTDPL grammar can be reduced to an equivalent TDPL grammar that recognizes the same language, although the process is not straightforward and may greatly increase the number of rules required.
[src:peg-parser/top-down-parsing-language] Also, both TDPL and GTDPL can be viewed as very restricted forms of parsing expression grammars, all of which represent the same class of grammars.
